// Transparent smoke surface hook fragment. Demonstrates a per-material color transform expressed as a hook (not
// a compile-time variant): the base color is square-root transformed and warm-tinted. The cook wraps it with the
// engine pixel-shader authoring + this material's typed .bind to generate the G-buffer pixel shader.
#include "smoke_material_color.slangi"


////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////


NwbMeshSurface nwbMaterialSurface(){
    const NwbMeshInstanceData instance = nwbMeshLoadInstance();
    const NwbSmokeSurfaceMaterial surface = nwbMaterialBindLoadSurface(instance);
    const NwbSmokeRuntimeMaterial runtime = nwbMaterialBindLoadRuntime(instance);
    const half4 tinted = half4(surface.base_color * runtime.color_tint);
    const half3 baseColor = nwbSmokeMaterialVertexColor(tinted.rgb);
    // ONE authored transparency, two consistent consumers: `density` (the tint's ALPHA channel) = how solid the glass
    // is, and `tint` (the tint RGB) = the colour its shadow keeps when solid. nwbMakeGlassSurface seeds BOTH from them
    // -- renderCoverage (the AVBOIT opacity all three passes read) = density, and shadowAbsorptionTint =
    // lerp(white, tint, density) -- so a solid glass is opaque on screen AND casts a matching coloured shadow. A bright
    // tint means a light glass and a faint shadow; pick a DARKER/more-saturated tint for a darker shadow. The ENGINE
    // still integrates the shadow over the true entry->exit volume path (per-crossing Fresnel from refractionIor +
    // signed Beer-Lambert), since only the trace sees both faces. To DELIBERATELY decouple the look from the shadow,
    // set result.renderCoverage after this call --
    // a visible, intentional exception. The base color stays the rasterized appearance (the G-buffer discards the
    // optical params + coverage).
    return nwbMakeGlassSurface(baseColor, inNormal, NWB_SURFACE_IOR_GLASS, tinted.rgb, tinted.a);
}


////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////

